    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. it just feels like there are a lot of ways things could go wrong. is there like a way to identify if a clause is being intentionally sneaky or trying to hide extra liabilities? i'm worried about \"hidden\" risks that aren't super obvious on first read.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When reviewing these documents, always look for the language that is overly broad or uses catch-all phrases like \"any and all losses.\" Sneaky clauses often hide in the scope of what you are responsible for, making sure the risk falls entirely on you, the Recipient. It's wise to scrutinize the definitions of \"breach\" and \"negligence\" to see if they are defined narrowly or vaguely. If the language feels too absolute, it probably is, and you should ask for clarification before signing.",
      "source": "target",
